This is a list of countries (and some territories) by the annual prevalence of [[opiate]]s [[Recreational drug use|use]] as percentage of the population aged 15–64 (unless otherwise indicated).
The primary source of information are the ''World Drug Report 2011'' (WDR 2011) and the ''World Drug Report 2006'' (WDR 2006),<ref name="wdr_2011">{{cite web| title=World Drug Report 2011 | url = http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/WDR2011/StatAnnex-consumption.pdf | year = 2011 | publisher = United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}}</ref><ref name="wdr_2006">{{cite web| title=World Drug Report 2006 | url = http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/WDR-2006.html | year = 2006 | publisher = United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}}</ref> published by the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] (UNODC). The indicator is the "annual prevalence" rate which is shown as the percentage of the youth and adult population who have consumed the drugs at least once in the past year. [[Opium production in Afghanistan|The largest producer of opiates]] in the world is Afghanistan to a total of 93% of the world's market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/wdr/WDR_2009/WDR2009_eng_web.pdf|title=World Drug Report 2009|publisher=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}}</ref>
The list does not include [[opioids]], which is classified as a different drug under the ''World Drug Report 2011'' list, which is considered "opiates and prescription opioids."
