'''Ray Hudson''', [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]], [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences|FAcSS]] (born 7 March 1948) is a British academic. He holds the degrees of PhD and DSc from Bristol University and. DLitt from Durham University. He is Professor of Geography and [[Deputy Vice-Chancellor]] at [[Durham University]].<ref name="bio - British Academy">{{cite web|title=HUDSON, Professor Ray|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/ord.cfm?member=5394|work=British Academy Fellows|publisher=British Academy|accessdate=5 March 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305170043/http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/directory/ord.cfm?member=5394|archivedate=5 March 2014|df=}}</ref><ref name="bio - Durham Geography">{{cite web|title=Professor Ray Hudson, BA, PhD, DLitt, DSC|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/geography/staff/geogstaffhidden/?id=345|work=Staff Profile|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> From 2014-2015  he was acting [[List of Vice-Chancellor & Wardens of Durham University|Vice-Chancellor and Warden]] of Durham University. Currently he remains as Professor of Geography.

==Academic career==
A [[Human geography|human geographer]], Hudson is a specialist in [[Development geography|developmental]], [[Economic geography|economic]], [[Political geography|political]] and [[Electoral geography|electoral]] geography.<ref name="bio - British Academy" /> He has published extensively on these issues, as author or editor of over 20 books and the author or co-author of over 100 journal articles and book chapters.

In 1972, he became a [[lecturer]] in the Department of Geography, [[Durham University]].<ref name="bio - Durham Geography" /> He was promoted to [[senior lecturer]] in 1984 and to [[Reader (academic rank)|reader]] in 1987.<ref name="bio - Durham Council" /> He was promoted to [[professor]] in 1990.<ref name="bio - Durham Geography" /> He was head of the Department of Geography from 1992 to 1997<ref name="bio - Durham Geography" /> From 2003 to 2007, he was Director of the [[Wolfson Research Institute]], a [[multi-disciplinary]] [[research institute]] specialising in health and well-being.<ref name="bio - Durham Council">{{cite web|title=Ray Hudson, BA PhD DSc DLitt FBA|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/committees/council/membership/current/hudson/|work=Council membership|publisher=Durham University|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306192140/https://www.dur.ac.uk/committees/council/membership/current/hudson/|archivedate=2014-03-06|df=}}</ref> In 2007, he was appointed [[Pro-Vice-Chancellor]] of partnerships and engagement.<ref name="bio - Durham Council" /> In 2012, he was appointed [[Deputy Vice-Chancellor]] of the university, becoming the second most senior academic.<ref name="bio - British Academy" /> From September 2014 to September 2015, he was acting [[List of Vice-Chancellor & Wardens of Durham University|Vice-Chancellor and Warden]] of Durham University. He stood down when Professor [[Stuart Corbridge]] took up the appointment and as Deputy Vice Chancellor in April 2016..<ref name="THE - LSE deputy director Stuart Corbridge to be Durham v-c">{{cite news|last1=Grove|first1=Jack|title=LSE deputy director Stuart Corbridge to be Durham v-c|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/lse-deputy-director-stuart-corbridge-to-be-durham-v-c/2019373.article|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=Times Higher Education|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> He is currently a visiting professor at University College Dublin and an honorary professor at Cardiff University.

==Honours==
In 2005, Hudson was awarded the [[Victoria Medal (geography)|Victoria Medal]] by the [[Royal Geographical Society]] 'for research on regional and industrial change in the UK and wider Europe'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medals and Awards|url=http://www.rgs.org/NR/rdonlyres/42561FD8-2BE0-4F1E-A64E-9D1680527BB0/0/MedalsandAwards2005Recipients.pdf|publisher=Royal Geographical Society|accessdate=5 March 2014|format=pdf|year=2005}}</ref> He was awarded the Sir Peter Hall award by the Regional Studies  Association in 2014. In 2006, he was elected [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA).<ref name="bio - British Academy" /> He was also elected a Member of the European Economy (Academia Europaea) in 2007,and is  an elected Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society, of the Regional Studies Association and of the [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences|Academy of Social Sciences]] (FAcSS).<ref>{{cite web|title=Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences|url=http://acss.org.uk/fellows/|publisher=Academy of Social Sciences|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> In 1987 he was awarded an honorary DSc by Roskilde University.

